\"role\": \"system\", \n                \"content\": (\n                    \"You are a helpful corporate policy assistant. Answer the user question strictly using the document context provided. \"\n                    \"If you cannot find the answer explicitly inside the context, reply exactly with: \"\n                    \"'I am sorry, but I cannot find an official guideline for that request in our documentation. Please contact the HR department.'\\n\\n\"\n                    f\"OFFICIAL DOCUMENT CONTEXT:\\n{reference_context}\"\n                )\n            },\n            {\"role\": \"user\", \"content\": employee_question}\n        ]\n        \n        # 4. Format prompt through tokenizer template rules\n        formatted_prompt = tokenizer.apply_chat_template(\n            chat_prompt,\n            tokenize=False,\n            add_generation_prompt=True\n        )\n        \n        # 5. Explicitly cast inputs directly to your active GPU accelerator device\n        model_inputs = tokenizer([formatted_prompt], return_tensors=\"pt\").to(model.device)\n        \n        # 6. Direct tensor execution bypassing generic pipeline wrappers\n        print(\"⚡ Processing inference weights on GPU...\")\n        generated_ids = model.generate(\n            **model_inputs,\n            max_new_tokens=400,\n            do_sample=False,       # Strict deterministic response selection\n            pad_token_id=tokenizer.eos_token_id\n        )\n        \n        # 7. Extract and isolate newborn response tokens\n        generated_ids = [\n            output_ids[len(input_ids):] for input_ids, output_ids in zip(model_inputs.input_ids, generated_ids)\n        ]\n        \n        clean_ai_output = tokenizer.batch_decode(generated_ids, skip_special_tokens=True)[0].strip()\n        return clean_ai_output\n\n    except Exception as error_msg:\n        return f\"❌ System execution runtime bottleneck: {str(error_msg)}\"\n\nprint(\"🧠 Upgraded RAG engine compiled successfully!\")","metadata":{"trusted":true,"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2026-06-09T20:57:18.121219Z","iopub.execute_input":"2026-06-09T20:57:18.121705Z","iopub.status.idle":"2026-06-09T20:57:18.133523Z","shell.execute_reply.started":"2026-06-09T20:57:18.121666Z","shell.execute_reply":"2026-06-09T20:57:18.132569Z"}},"outputs":[{"name":"stdout","text":"🧠 Upgraded RAG engine compiled successfully!\n","output_type":"stream"}],"execution_count":4},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"### 🔍 Step 4B: Isolated Pipeline Validation & Integration Testing\nThis code acts as a direct integration test to validate the complete Retrieval-Augmented Generation (RAG) loop entirely in the terminal, completely detached from the web UI layer. It provides a step-by-step console trace that safely flushes GPU memory caches, embeds a test query, extracts raw context directly from the Chroma vector space, and runs a zero-propagation forward pass (`torch.no_grad()`) through the LLM to verify retrieval alignment and deterministic response quality.","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"# =====================================================================\n# DIRECT RAG PIPELINE VALIDATION TEST\n# =====================================================================\nimport torch\nimport gc\n\ndef test_rag_pipeline(sample_question):\n    print(f\"🔍 Question: '{sample_question}'\")\n    print(\"-\" * 60)\n    \n    # 1. Clear GPU memory caches up front\n    gc.collect()\n    if torch.cuda.is_available():\n        torch.cuda.empty_cache()\n        \n    try:\n        # 2. Vectorize the test question\n        print(\"🧠 1/4: Embedding question...\")\n        question_vector = embedding_model.encode(sample_question).tolist()\n        \n        # 3. Retrieve relevant pieces from your company rules PDF\n        print(\"📁 2/4: Querying persistent vector database...\")\n        search_results = policy_collection.query(\n            query_embeddings=[question_vector],\n            n_results=2\n        )\n        \n        extracted_nodes = search_results['documents'][0]\n        reference_context = \"\\n---\\n\".join(extracted_nodes)\n        \n        print(\"\\n[Retrieved Context Preview]\")\n        print(reference_context[:300] + \"...\\n\" if len(reference_context) > 300 else reference_context)\n        print(\"-\" * 60)\n        \n        # 4. Construct the prompt sequence\n        chat_prompt = [\n            {\n                \"role\": \"system\", \n                \"content\": f\"Answer the user question strictly using the provided context.\\n\\nCONTEXT:\\n{reference_context}\"\n            },\n            {\"role\": \"user\", \"content\": sample_question}\n        ]\n        \n        formatted_prompt = tokenizer.apply_chat_template(\n            chat_prompt,\n            tokenize=False,\n            add_generation_prompt=True\n        )\n        \n        # 5. Tokenize and execute raw model inference on your GPU\n        print(\"⚡ 3/4: Processing generation weights on GPU...\")\n        inputs = tokenizer([formatted_prompt], return_tensors=\"pt\")\n        inputs = {k: v.to(model.device) for k, v in inputs.items()}\n        \n        with torch.no_grad():\n            generated_ids = model.generate(\n                **inputs,\n                max_new_tokens=250,\n                do_sample=False,\n                pad_token_id=tokenizer.eos_token_id\n            )\n            \n        # Isolate and decode newly generated text tokens\n        generated_ids = [\n            output_ids[len(input_ids):] for input_ids, output_ids in zip(inputs[\"input_ids\"], generated_ids)\n        ]\n        \n        ai_response = tokenizer.batch_decode(generated_ids, skip_special_tokens=True)[0].strip()\n        \n        print(\"✨ 4/4: Final AI Response:\")\n        print(\"=\" * 60)\n        print(ai_response)\n        print(\"=\" * 60)\n        \n    except Exception as e:\n        print(f\"❌ Pipeline Failed! Error details: {str(e)}\")\n\n# =====================================================================\n# RUN THE TEST\n# =====================================================================\n# Change this question to match anything actually written inside your company_rules.pdf\ntest_query = \"What are the official working hours?\"\ntest_rag_pipeline(test_query)","metadata":{"trusted":true,"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2026-06-09T21:01:35.782857Z","iopub.execute_input":"2026-06-09T21:01:35.783391Z","iopub.status.idle":"2026-06-09T21:03:02.19125Z","shell.execute_reply.started":"2026-06-09T21:01:35.783353Z","shell.execute_reply":"2026-06-09T21:03:02.190173Z"}},"outputs":[{"name":"stdout","text":"🔍 Question: 'What are the official working hours?'\n------------------------------------------------------------\n🧠 1/4: Embedding question...\n📁 2/4: Querying persistent vector database...\n\n[Retrieved Context Preview]\n## Article [83]\n\n## Minutes of Board Meetings\n---\n1. The Minister and the CMA's board shall, within their respective areas of competence, issue the regulations not later than [180] days following the publication date of the law. Such regulations shall specify the rules, timeframes, procedures and th...\n\n------------------------------------------------------------\n⚡ 3/4: Processing generation weights on GPU...\n⚡ Processing inference weights on GPU...\n✨ 4/4: Final AI Response:\n============================================================\nThe official working hours mentioned in the given text are 24/7, as indicated by \"not later than [180] days following the publication date of the law.\" This suggests that the regulations will be issued without any specific mention of a particular start or end time, implying they operate continuously throughout the day. However, it is important to note that this information pertains specifically to the issuance of regulations under the law, which may have different operational requirements depending on the jurisdiction and the nature of the law itself.\n============================================================\n⚡ Processing inference weights on GPU...\n","output_type":"stream"}],"execution_count":9},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"### 🕵️‍♂️ Step 4C: Deep Pipeline Inspection & Context Window Optimization\nThis cell provides a diagnostic, high-visibility debugging function designed to trace and tune vector database retrieval parameters. By scaling the retrieval window up to 5 concurrent document fragments (`n_results=5`), it systematically prints raw text block previews to audit chunk matching behavior. Additionally, it injects explicit token parameter overrides (`max_length=None`) straight into the model execution pass to neutralize hidden tokenizer configuration warnings and ensure flawless GPU generation formatting.","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"# =====================================================================\n# DEEP PIPELINE INSPECTION (INCREASED RETRIEVAL WINDOW)\n# =====================================================================\ndef dynamic_pipeline_test(sample_question):\n    print(f\"🔍 Testing Question: '{sample_question}'\")\n    print(\"-\" * 60)\n    \n    # 1. Vectorize query\n    question_vector = embedding_model.encode(sample_question).tolist()\n    \n    # 2. Pull 5 chunks instead of 2 to catch hidden document sections\n    search_results = policy_collection.query(\n        query_embeddings=[question_vector],\n        n_results=5\n    )\n    \n    extracted_nodes = search_results['documents'][0]\n    \n    print(f\"📋 Chroma found {len(extracted_nodes)} matching blocks. Printing snippets:\")\n    for idx, node in enumerate(extracted_nodes):\n        print(f\"\\n--- [Block #{idx + 1}] ---\")\n        print(node[:200] + \"...\")\n        \n    reference_context = \"\\n---\\n\".join(extracted_nodes)\n    print(\"-\" * 60)\n    \n    # 3. Instruction generation with explicit max_length override to clear transformers log warnings\n    chat_prompt = [\n        {\"role\": \"system\", \"content\": f\"Answer the question using the context. If the context doesn't contain the answer, say 'Not found in text'.\\n\\nCONTEXT:\\n{reference_context}\"},\n        {\"role\": \"user\", \"content\": sample_question}\n    ]\n    \n    formatted_prompt = tokenizer.apply_chat_template(chat_prompt, tokenize=False, add_generation_prompt=True)\n    inputs = tokenizer([formatted_prompt], return_tensors=\"pt\")\n    inputs = {k: v.to(model.device) for k, v in inputs.items()}\n    \n    with torch.no_grad():\n        generated_ids = model.generate(\n            **inputs,\n            max_new_tokens=250,\n            max_length=None, # Explicitly clear transformers conflict warning\n            do_sample=False,\n            pad_token_id=tokenizer.eos_token_id\n        )\n        \n    generated_ids = [output_ids[len(input_ids):] for input_ids, output_ids in zip(inputs[\"input_ids\"], generated_ids)]\n    ai_response = tokenizer.batch_decode(generated_ids, skip_special_tokens=True)[0].strip()\n    \n    print(\"\\n✨ Pipeline Output:\")\n    print(ai_response)\n\n# Run a test query based on what we know is actually inside your document:\ndynamic_pipeline_test(\"What is the timeframe for the board to issue regulations?\")","metadata":{"trusted":true,"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2026-06-09T20:58:03.246844Z","iopub.execute_input":"2026-06-09T20:58:03.247393Z","iopub.status.idle":"2026-06-09T20:59:04.671651Z"}},"outputs":[{"name":"stdout","text":"🔍 Testing Question: 'What is the timeframe for the board to issue regulations?'\n------------------------------------------------------------\n📋 Chroma found 5 matching blocks. Printing snippets:\n\n--- [Block #1] ---\n1. The Minister and the CMA's board shall, within their respective areas of competence, issue the regulations not later than [180] days following the publication date of the law. Such regulations shal...\n\n--- [Block #2] ---\nreport, if any, shall be submitted to the shareholders, within [six] months following the date of the en